                <li>PCR tests are usually sent to a lab for processing, and the results can take several days to arrive. This schedule is less likely to work when you have a one-day window to get tested AND receive results before flying. </li>
                <li>An antigen test, which can provide results in 15 to 30 minutes, is preferable. However, not all antigen testing comply with the CDC's directive. </li>
                <li>A qualifying antigen test, according to the CDC, must contain a telehealth service linked with the test's manufacturer that provides real-time monitoring remotely over an audio and video connection. Put another way, and you will need someone to see you take your test if you want it to be accepted. </li>
